&#13;
			<div id="ftn12">&#13;
				<p><b><b><i><i><a href="#_ftnref12" name="_ftn12" id="_ftn12"><span class="MsoFootnoteReference"><span><span class="MsoFootnoteReference"><span>[12]</span></span></span></span></a> Other countries that criminalize cross-dressing or posing as the opposite sex include Kuwait, Nigeria, Guyana, Tonga, and Italy. In Kuwait, a provision of the Penal Code prohibits imitating the opposite sex in any way. See generally, Human Rights Watch, <i>They Hunt Us Down for Fun</i>: <i>Discrimination and Police Violence Against Transgender Women in Kuwait, </i>January 2011, http://www.hrw.org/sites/default/files/reports/kuwait0112ForUpload.pdf. A 2013 court ruling in Guyana found Guyanas cross-dressing laws to be unconstitutional, but ruled that cross-dressing could still be prohibited if for immoral purposes. Neil Marks, Guyana court rules cross-dressing is not a crime, Reuters, September 9, 2013, http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/09/us-guyana-crossdressing-idUSBRE98811V20130909 (accessed May 29, 2014). In Nigeria, several states sharia enactments criminalize trans people: for instance, a law in Kano that prohibits <span>indecent dress that is against the practice of Islam has been used against transwomen, and Bauchi state prohibits men dressing as women. Islamic police arrest 150 in Nigeria accused of indecent dress, prostitution and cross-dressing, <i>The Telegraph</i>, October 23, 2013, http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/nigeria/10398365/Islamic-police-arrest-150-in-Nigeria-accused-of-indecent-dress-prostitution-and-cross-dressing.html (accessed August 7, 2014); Nigeria </span>Islamic court tries 18 for cross-dressing , Reuters, August 22, 2007, http://www.stuff.co.nz/oddstuff/7578/Nigerian-Islamic-court-tries-18-for-cross-dressing/ (accessed August 7, 2014). The law in Tonga that prohibits males from impersonating females have never been enforced. Sue Farran and Alexander Sua, Criminal Law and <i>Faafafine </i>and <i>Fakaleiti </i>in the South Pacific, <i>Journal of South Pacific Law</i>, Vol. 9, Issue 1, 2005, http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=13297 (accessed June 16, 2014). Samoa decriminalized cross-dressing in 2013. See: Anna Leach, Impersonating a woman decriminalized in Samoa, post to images on concrete words on paper (blog), May 2, 2013, http://imagesonconcretewordsonpaper.wordpress.com/2013/05/02/impersonating-a-woman-decriminalized-in-samoa/ (accessed June 16, 2014). An Italian ordinance against unauthorized wearing of disguises has been used to prosecute transwomenthe last known case was in 1976and laws against cross-dressing are on the books in Paris, but are not enforced. Email communication from Carla LaGata, Transgender Europe, to Human Rights Watch, June 14, 2014. In the United Arab Emirates, a vague law on indecent acts, article 358 of the Penal Code, is used regularly to convict transgender people or people who are cross-dressing. See, for example, Salam al Amir, Filipino fashion professionals jailed for cross-dressing in Dubai, <i>The National</i>, June 17, 2014, http://www.thenational.ae/uae/courts/filipino-fashion-professionals-jailed-for-crossdressing-in-dubai (accessed June 17, 2014). Saudi Arabia has arrested and sentenced people to flogging and imprisonment for cross-dressing, despite having no written law prohibiting it. See: Human Rights Watch, Saudi Arabia: Drop Cross-Dressing Charges, June 24, 2009, http://www.hrw.org/news/2009/06/24/saudi-arabia-drop-cross-dressing-charges.</i></i></b></b></p>&#13;
			</div>&#13;
&#13;
			<div id="ftn13">&#13;
				<p><b><b><i><i><a href="#_ftnref13" name="_ftn13" id="_ftn13"><span class="MsoFootnoteReference"><span><span class="MsoFootnoteReference"><span>[13]</span></span></span></span></a> Such fatwas exist in Johor, Kedah, Kelantan, Malacca, Pahang, Perak, and Sarawak. They have been gazetted in Johor, Kedah, Malacca, and Perak. See: http://www.e-fatwa.gov.my/ (accessed June 25, 2014).</i></i></b></b></p>&#13;
